<ul>\n\t<li><strong>USD/JPY keeps the previous day&rsquo;s break of 106.00 despite recently easing from 106.06.</strong></li>\n\t<li><strong>Risk sentiment remains mildly positive as US President Trump tries to regain market confidence with stimulus, vaccine hopes.</strong></li>\n\t<li><strong>Japan&rsquo;s trade and current account numbers flashed welcome data for August.</strong></li>\n\t<li><strong>US VP debate, Japan&rsquo;s Eco Watchers Survey will be the key.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>USD/JPY stays positive at around 106.10 as markets in Tokyo open for Thursday&rsquo;s trading. In doing so, the pair struggles to justify the recent risk-on mood and upbeat data from Japan ahead of US Vice Presidential (VP) Debate.</p>\n\n<p>Japan&rsquo;s August month&rsquo;s Current Account balance grew past- &yen;1983.7 B forecast to &yen;2102.8 B. Also on the positive side is Trade Balance &ndash; BOP Basis that rose beyond &yen;137.3 B previous readouts to &yen;413.2 B.</p>\n\n<h2 class="fxs_headline_medium">Traders&rsquo; doubt on Trump&rsquo;s optimism&hellip;</h2>\n\n<p><a href="https://www.fxstreet.com/economic-calendar/united-states">US</a> President Donald Trump recently said he feels perfect and the coronavirus (COVID-19) vaccine will be out just after the November month&rsquo;s election, due to the political problems. The Republican chief is also ready to consider the Democrats&rsquo; counterproposal, as per the White House Chief of Staff Mark Meadows, if House Speaker Nancy Pelosi respects the administration&rsquo;s stand. However, market players are less convinced as there is very little time before the world&rsquo;s largest economy head to the Presidential election. The political drama has already taken a long time and is still failing to offer any stimulus, which in turn adds to the odds of opposing Trump&rsquo;s upbeat sentiment.</p>\n\n<p>It&rsquo;s worth mentioning that the <a href="https://www.fxstreet.com/news">news</a> from Yomiuri suggests Japan will remove the travel ban for 12 countries including China from next month also added to the market-positive points but failed to lure the bulls. Also, the <a href="https://www.fxstreet.com/macroeconomics/central-banks/fed">Fed</a> minutes and recent comments from US central bank policymakers have been trying to negate any pessimism.</p>\n\n<p>Against this backdrop, Japan&rsquo;s <a href="https://www.fxstreet.com/rates-charts/nikkei225">Nikkei 225</a> rises 0.40% to reach near to the pre-pandemic era whereas S&amp;P 500 Futures add 0.20% gains to 3,413 by the time of the press.</p>\n\n<p>Looking forward, the US Vice Presidential Debate, at 01:00 GMT, will be an immediate catalyst and is likely to offer another positive signal to the risk tone. Following that, Japan&rsquo;s Eco Watchers Survey for September and the US Jobless Claims will join hands with the risk factors to entertain markets.</p>\n\n<h3 class="fxs_headline_medium">Technical analysis</h3>\n\n<p>A sustained break of 50-day SMA, currently near 105.85, can keep the bulls directed towards the September month high of 106.55.</p>\n\n<div class="ktldata_cke
